<BaseLayout
  title="Protestantism — The Priesthood — Nazaryah"
  description="The Reformers walked out of Rome's house carrying a suitcase full of Rome's clothing. They threw out some of her doctrines but kept many others. The Reformation was never finished."
>
  <div class="al-wrap">

    <!-- ── HERO ── -->
    <section class="al-hero">
      <a href="/sun-worship/the-priesthood/the-institutional-church" class="al-back">&#8592; Back to The Institutional Church</a>
      <p class="al-label">&#8213; The Priesthood · Full Study &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="al-title">Protestantism</h1>
      <p class="al-sub">
        The Half-Finished Reformation
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── ARTICLE BODY ── -->
    <article class="al-article">
      <div class="al-inner">

        <!-- Opening -->
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            When Martin Luther nailed his Ninety-Five Theses to the door of the Wittenberg church in 1517, he sparked what is called the Protestant Reformation. Luther saw real corruption in the Catholic Church — the selling of indulgences, the worship of relics, the obvious greed of the Pope — and he protested. So did Calvin, Zwingli, and many others who came after him. They broke away from Rome and started new churches. We call those churches Protestant because they protested.
          </p>
          <p>
            But the Reformation was not finished. It only went halfway. The Reformers walked out of Rome's house carrying a suitcase full of Rome's clothing. They threw out some of her doctrines but kept many others. They protested her authority but adopted her practices. Today, more than 30,000 Protestant denominations exist around the world, all claiming to follow Scripture alone, and yet almost every one of them still wears Catholic clothes. To leave Babylon completely, you have to know what she handed to her daughters.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">The Sun Day</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            Start with the day of worship. The fourth commandment in Exodus 20:8–11 says, "Remember the Sabbath day, to keep it holy." The Sabbath is the seventh day of the week — what we now call Saturday. Yahuah set it apart at creation, before there was a Jew or a Gentile (Genesis 2:2–3). He commanded it forever. Yahushua kept it. The apostles kept it. The early believers kept it for hundreds of years.
          </p>
          <p>
            So why does almost every Protestant church meet on Sunday? Because the Catholic Church changed it. In the year 321, the Roman Emperor Constantine — who was a worshiper of the sun god Sol Invictus — issued a law that all people in the empire should rest on "the venerable day of the Sun." Those are his exact words. The Catholic Church later confirmed this change at the Council of Laodicea in 364, even cursing those who continued to keep the seventh-day Sabbath. The Catholic Church openly admits they made this change. In their own catechisms, they boast that the change of the Sabbath is the mark of their authority over Scripture.
          </p>
          <p>
            When the Reformers left Rome, they kept her sun day. Luther kept it. Calvin kept it. Wesley kept it. Today, almost every Baptist, Methodist, Presbyterian, Pentecostal, Lutheran, and non-denominational church in the world keeps it. They have replaced the commandment of Yahuah with the tradition of men, exactly as Yahushua warned about in Mark 7:7–9. Every Sunday morning, hundreds of millions of people who claim to follow the Messiah are unknowingly honoring the day dedicated to the sun.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">The Trinity</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            The trinity is another piece of Catholic baggage that the Reformers carried out the door. The doctrine that Yahuah is "three persons in one being" was hammered out at the Council of Nicaea in 325, again under Constantine, and finalized at the Council of Constantinople in 381. The word "trinity" appears nowhere in Scripture. The phrase "three persons in one being" appears nowhere in Scripture. What you find in Scripture is one Yahuah, our Father, and one Lord, Yahushua the Messiah, the Son of Yahuah, who is the image of the invisible Father (Colossians 1:15) and the express image of His person (Hebrews 1:3). The Holy Spirit is the Spirit of Yahuah, the Father's own Spirit poured out, not a third separate person. Deuteronomy 6:4 declares, "Hear, O Israel: Yahuah our Elohim is one Yahuah." Yahushua quoted this as the greatest commandment (Mark 12:29). One. Not three.
          </p>
          <p>
            The Reformers kept the trinity. They wrote it into their confessions. They burned and drowned anyone who denied it. John Calvin had Michael Servetus burned alive at the stake in Geneva in 1553 for rejecting the trinity. The Reformers protested some of Rome's doctrines but defended her crown jewel with the same violence Rome had used. The blood is on their hands, and the false doctrine is on their pulpits.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">The Pagan Holidays</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            The pagan holidays came along too. Christmas on December 25 has nothing to do with the birth of Yahushua, who was almost certainly born during the Feast of Tabernacles in the fall. December 25 was the birthday of Sol Invictus, the unconquered sun, and fell during the Roman festival of Saturnalia. The Catholic Church baptized these pagan dates and called them Christian. The Reformers kept them. The Christmas tree itself is condemned by name in Jeremiah 10:2–4, which warns against cutting down a tree, decorating it with silver and gold, and setting it up in your house — "the customs of the people are vain."
          </p>
          <p>
            Easter is even worse. The very name comes from Ishtar, the Babylonian goddess of fertility, sex, and war. Her symbols were eggs and rabbits — exactly what shows up on Easter morning. Yahushua did not rise on Easter. He rose during the Feast of Firstfruits, an appointed time of Yahuah commanded in Leviticus 23. The Reformers kept Easter. Most Protestant churches still do, never asking why they are decorating eggs and hunting rabbits in the name of the risen Messiah.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">Replacement Theology</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            Replacement theology is another Catholic invention the Protestants kept. This is the idea that the Church has replaced Israel, that Yahuah is done with His people, and that all the promises and commandments given to Israel now belong to a Gentile institution. This was developed by Catholic theologians like Augustine. It was used for centuries to justify the persecution of Jews and the rejection of Torah. The Reformers kept it. Even today, most Protestant pulpits teach that the law was for the Jews and grace is for the Christians, completely ignoring that Yahushua said, "Think not that I am come to destroy the law, or the prophets: I am not come to destroy, but to fulfil" (Matthew 5:17).
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">The Lawless Gospel</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            This leads to the worst Protestant doctrine of all — antinomianism, the idea that the law was nailed to the cross. Protestants love the verse "you are not under the law but under grace" (Romans 6:14), but they read it backward. Paul is saying that grace is the means by which we are now able to keep the law, not an excuse to throw it away. He says in the very next verse, "What then? shall we sin because we are not under the law, but under grace? Yahuah forbid." Sin is the breaking of the law (1 John 3:4). If grace abolished the law, there would be no sin to be saved from. The Protestant gospel of "grace without obedience" is the gospel of the serpent — "ye shall not surely die" (Genesis 3:4).
          </p>
          <p>
            True salvation comes through faith in the Messiah alone. Yahushua paid the price no one else could pay. But once a person has been saved, they are called to walk as He walked (1 John 2:6) — and He walked in perfect obedience to His Father's Torah. Salvation is the door. Torah is the path you walk after you go through the door. The Protestant church has bricked up the path and pretended there was nothing on the other side of the door.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">The Other Catholic Seeds</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            Other Catholic seeds in Protestant soil include infant baptism, which most denominations still practice even though there is no biblical example of it. The pre-tribulation rapture is a 19th-century invention by John Nelson Darby that has nothing to do with Scripture. Once-saved-always-saved contradicts dozens of warnings in the New Testament about falling away (Hebrews 6:4–6, Hebrews 10:26–29, 2 Peter 2:20–22). The use of the title "Lord" in place of the Father's name Yahuah, and the Greek-Latin name "Jesus Christ" instead of the Hebrew name Yahushua Messiah, both came down through Rome. Each is a piece of Roman clothing that the Reformation forgot to take off.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">Even the Sabbath Keepers Carry It</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            Even those who keep the seventh-day Sabbath often kept the rest of Rome's package. The Seventh-day Adventist Church, for example, recognizes the Sabbath but holds tightly to the trinity, follows the writings of Ellen G. White as a "modern prophet," and in many cases still celebrates Christmas and Easter. Other Sabbath-keeping groups have similar issues. Keeping the right day is necessary, but it is not enough. To leave Babylon, you have to leave all of her — not just the calendar.
          </p>
          <p>
            A church can meet on the seventh day and still be drinking from the harlot's cup if they have kept her doctrines. The day is necessary but not sufficient. The full call is to come out of her sins, her teachings, her holidays, her hierarchy, her trinity, her replacement theology, and her watered-down lawless gospel.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="al-h2">Come Out of Her</h2>
        <div class="al-prose">
          <p>
            This is the call of Revelation 18:4 — "Come out of her, my people, that ye be not partakers of her sins, and that ye receive not of her plagues." Yahuah is not telling His people to come out of Catholicism only. He is telling them to come out of the entire Babylonian system, including her Protestant daughters. Sunday worship, the trinity, Christmas, Easter, replacement theology, antinomianism, the rapture, and the rest must all be left behind.
          </p>
          <p>
            The good news is that there is a remnant. There are believers all over the world waking up, throwing off Rome's clothing, returning to the name of the Father Yahuah and the Son Yahushua, keeping the true Sabbath, walking in Torah, keeping the appointed times, and living as set-apart people. They are not perfect, but they are coming out. They are answering the call.
          </p>
          <p>
            The question for every Protestant reading this is simple: will you stay in your grandmother's denomination because it feels familiar, or will you follow the Messiah even if it costs you everything? The Reformation was a beginning. It was never meant to be the end. It is time to finish what Luther started — and to finish it the right way, by going all the way back to the Scriptures, all the way back to Torah, and all the way back to the names and ways of the Father and His Son.
          </p>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="al-quote al-quote-closing">
          <p class="al-quote-ref">Revelation 18:4</p>
          <p>"Come out of her, my people, that ye be not partakers of her sins, and that ye receive not of her plagues."</p>
        </blockquote>

